<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-883-744  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 883 744.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Nov 13 1989 n274 pC11(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>William McGowan: Chairman and CEO, MCI Communications Corp. (Top25 influential figures in communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lynch, Karen; Schultz, Beth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>William McGowan is Chairman and CEO of MCI Communications Corp,which currently claims a 12 percent share of the UStelecommunications market, amounting to $5 billion in revenue andprofits of $346 million in 1988.andP;  McGowan, known as an intensecompetitor, became involved in a dispute over microwave radioservice licensing in 1968.andP;  The fight led to the formation ofMicrowave Communications, later MCI, in 1971.andP;  Over the nextdecade, McGowan won a series of court victories in which hecontested A T and T's monopoly status.andP;  These actions culminatedin the famous divestiture agreement of 1982.andP;  Today, MCI and A Tand T are involved in an intense competition which has spread tothe arena of international communications, where MCI's marketshare has grown to 15 percent of the total.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (officials and employees)American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (cases).andO;Ticker:    T; MCIC.andO;Topic:     CompetitionCommunications Service SuppliersMarket ShareMicrowave Communications.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   William McGowan. (portrait)Person:    McGowan, William G. (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>